      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Great Debaters (Starting in School)</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Denton letter praises Lincoln-Douglas Debates for students</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Resolved: That High School Debate Is Back'' (Education page, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Resolved: That High School Debate Is Back'' (Education page, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>In addition to policy debate, there is another format in which a large number of students take part: Lincoln-Douglas Debate, modeled after the great debates on slavery. Regis High School, which I attend, fields a team of about 45 students in this category. The challenge of L.D., as it is commonly known, is that every two months, students must debate the moral and ethical values of a new resolution.</p>
        <p>For example, the present resolution examines the morality of prohibiting hate speech on college campuses. In the past, we have debated whether a single country can morally intervene in the domestic affairs of another.</p>
        <p>The moral focus in L.D. leads many students to read works by great philosophers. It encourages thought about issues and political systems, and it teaches us to explore what is right and wrong in a range of human activities.</p>
        <p>DAVID DENTON  Brooklyn, Oct. 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
